‚Ä¢ The parse error occurs because an existing alias named docs (e.g., alias docs='nocorrect') expands during parsing the function definition, turning docs() into invalid syntax like nocorrect(), causing a failure. To fix this,
  prefixing the function name with a backslash (e.g., \docs() {}) disables alias expansion and avoids the parse error. Alternatively, unaliasing docs before the function or disabling alias expansion in the script won't prevent
  the parse error as alias expansion happens during parsing, before any commands run.

  Considering converting to standalone script to avoid alias conflict

  Replacing the function definition with a standalone executable script using a shebang would bypass alias expansion issues by avoiding function wrappers entirely, allowing the script to run directly without triggering alias-
